  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A New Era
  author: Lee Jang-yong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Emperor's grace unfolds, reaching to the farthest corners—
    From the envoy's finest brush, ten thousand souls are reborn.
    Our sage lord receives the scholars of old with open heart,
    While courtly worthies bow and cry out, "Long live the Yuan!"

    Clear spirit matches a thousand stalks of snow-white hair,
    Wondrous words compete to pass on ten thousand pearls.

    Long have I revered your virtuous deeds from afar,
    Now, by fortune's grace, I stand before your face.
    I beg you, view this humble heart with compassion too—
    Let it follow the same path as all those greater souls.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem celebrates the new reign (元朝 refers to a new dynasty or era of rule) and the emperor's benevolent governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to the "envoy's brush" (使臣) suggests the poet may be writing in an official or ceremonial capacity, witnessing or participating in imperial proceedings.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of "snow-white hair" and "pearls" are traditional poetic symbols for wisdom and precious virtue in East Asian literary tradition.
